eal estate; known for visualizing where clients should live and seeing a home's potential."}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Slept under Kihn's Alice in Wonderland murals","body":"As a child she lived in her grandmother's 1688 wood-frame farmhouse in East Haddam, Connecticut, while her father restored the home and installed plumbing and central heat. The walls of her bedroom were painted with Alice in Wonderland murals by her uncle W. Langdon Kihn — the same painter who illustrated for National Geographic, where the murals were later profiled."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Survived the 1938 New England hurricane","body":"Her family survived the surprise 1938 hurricane that devastated the New England coast — she was three years old. Soon afterward the Bragdon family moved from Connecticut to St. Louis, where her paternal grandfather was a founding executive at D'Arcy Advertising and her father took an executive position at Carter Carburetor."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Wheaton over Rhode Island, then St. Louis television","body":"She dreamed of Rhode Island School of Design but her father insisted on the more practical Wheaton College, which failed to inspire her. She transferred to Washington University in St. Louis and married Dr. John Meyer in 1954. For a time she hosted a local television review of St. Louis attractions, then wrote for St. Louis magazine."},{"number":4,"category":"marriage","header":"Two marriages — second a real-estate partnership","body":"Her first marriage to Dr. John Meyer produced three children but ended in divorce in 1969. In 1970 she married Ethan Allen Hitchcock Shepley Jr., a B-17G radio operator with thirty-four missions over Germany, who encouraged her sharp eye into a residential real estate career. Their twenty-one years together 